1
00:00:11,820 --> 00:00:13,820
Chris Anderson: Julian, welcome.

2
00:00:13,820 --> 00:00:15,820
It's been reported that WikiLeaks, your baby,

3
00:00:15,820 --> 00:00:17,820
has, in the last few years

4
00:00:17,820 --> 00:00:20,820
has released more classified documents

5
00:00:20,820 --> 00:00:22,820
than the rest of the world's media combined.

6
00:00:22,820 --> 00:00:24,820
Can that possibly be true?

7
00:00:24,820 --> 00:00:26,820
Julian Assange: Yeah, can it possibly be true?

8
00:00:26,820 --> 00:00:29,820
It's a worry -- isn't it? -- that the rest of the world's media

9
00:00:29,820 --> 00:00:31,820
is doing such a bad job

10
00:00:31,820 --> 00:00:33,820
that a little group of activists

11
00:00:33,820 --> 00:00:35,820
is able to release more

12
00:00:35,820 --> 00:00:37,820
of that type of information

13
00:00:37,820 --> 00:00:39,820
than the rest of the world press combined.

14
00:00:39,820 --> 00:00:41,820
CA: How does it work?

15
00:00:41,820 --> 00:00:44,820
How do people release the documents?

16
00:00:44,820 --> 00:00:47,820
And how do you secure their privacy?

17
00:00:47,820 --> 00:00:49,820
JA: So these are -- as far as we can tell --

18
00:00:49,820 --> 00:00:51,820
classical whistleblowers,

19
00:00:51,820 --> 00:00:53,820
and we have a number of ways for them

20
00:00:53,820 --> 00:00:55,820
to get information to us.

21
00:00:55,820 --> 00:00:57,820
So we use this state-of-the-art encryption

22
00:00:57,820 --> 00:00:59,820
to bounce stuff around the Internet, to hide trails,

23
00:00:59,820 --> 00:01:01,820
pass it through legal jurisdictions

24
00:01:01,820 --> 00:01:04,820
like Sweden and Belgium

25
00:01:04,820 --> 00:01:07,820
to enact those legal protections.

26
00:01:08,820 --> 00:01:10,820
We get information in the mail,

27
00:01:10,820 --> 00:01:13,820
the regular postal mail,

28
00:01:13,820 --> 00:01:15,820
encrypted or not,

29
00:01:15,820 --> 00:01:18,820
vet it like a regular news organization, format it --

30
00:01:18,820 --> 00:01:21,820
which is sometimes something that's quite hard to do,

31
00:01:21,820 --> 00:01:23,820
when you're talking about

32
00:01:23,820 --> 00:01:25,820
giant databases of information --

33
00:01:25,820 --> 00:01:27,820
release it to the public

34
00:01:27,820 --> 00:01:29,820
and then defend ourselves

35
00:01:29,820 --> 00:01:32,820
against the inevitable legal and political attacks.

36
00:01:32,820 --> 00:01:34,820
CA: So you make an effort to ensure

37
00:01:34,820 --> 00:01:36,820
the documents are legitimate,

38
00:01:36,820 --> 00:01:38,820
but you actually

39
00:01:38,820 --> 00:01:41,820
almost never know who the identity of the source is?

40
00:01:41,820 --> 00:01:44,820
JA: That's right, yeah. Very rarely do we ever know,

41
00:01:45,820 --> 00:01:48,820
and if we find out at some stage

42
00:01:48,820 --> 00:01:51,820
then we destroy that information as soon as possible.

43
00:01:51,820 --> 00:01:53,820
(Phone ring) God damn it.

44
00:01:53,820 --> 00:01:57,820
(Laughter)

45
00:01:57,820 --> 00:01:59,820
CA: I think that's the CIA asking what the code is

46
00:01:59,820 --> 00:02:01,820
for a TED membership.

47
00:02:01,820 --> 00:02:04,820
(Laughter)

48
00:02:04,820 --> 00:02:06,820
So let's take [an] example, actually.

49
00:02:06,820 --> 00:02:08,820
This is something

50
00:02:08,820 --> 00:02:10,820
you leaked a few years ago.

51
00:02:10,820 --> 00:02:12,820
If we can have this document up ...

52
00:02:12,820 --> 00:02:14,820
So this was a story in Kenya a few years ago.

53
00:02:14,820 --> 00:02:17,820
Can you tell us what you leaked and what happened?

54
00:02:17,820 --> 00:02:19,820
JA: So this is the Kroll Report.

55
00:02:19,820 --> 00:02:22,820
This was a secret intelligence report

56
00:02:22,820 --> 00:02:24,820
commissioned by the Kenyan government

57
00:02:24,820 --> 00:02:27,820
after its election in 2004.

58
00:02:27,820 --> 00:02:29,820
Prior to 2004, Kenya was ruled

59
00:02:29,820 --> 00:02:31,820
by Daniel arap Moi

60
00:02:31,820 --> 00:02:33,820
for about 18 years.

61
00:02:33,820 --> 00:02:36,820
He was a soft dictator of Kenya.

62
00:02:36,820 --> 00:02:38,820
And when Kibaki got into power --

63
00:02:38,820 --> 00:02:40,820
through a coalition of forces that were trying

64
00:02:40,820 --> 00:02:42,820
to clean up corruption in Kenya --

65
00:02:42,820 --> 00:02:44,820
they commissioned this report,

66
00:02:44,820 --> 00:02:46,820
spent about two million pounds

67
00:02:46,820 --> 00:02:48,820
on this and an associated report.

68
00:02:48,820 --> 00:02:51,820
And then the government sat on it

69
00:02:51,820 --> 00:02:53,820
and used it for political leverage on Moi,

70
00:02:53,820 --> 00:02:55,820
who was the richest man --

71
00:02:55,820 --> 00:02:58,820
still is the richest man -- in Kenya.

72
00:02:58,820 --> 00:03:01,820
It's the Holy Grail of Kenyan journalism.

73
00:03:01,820 --> 00:03:04,820
So I went there in 2007,

74
00:03:04,820 --> 00:03:06,820
and we managed to get hold of this

75
00:03:06,820 --> 00:03:08,820
just prior to the election --

76
00:03:08,820 --> 00:03:11,820
the national election, December 28.

77
00:03:13,820 --> 00:03:16,820
When we released that report,

78
00:03:16,820 --> 00:03:19,820
we did so three days after the new president, Kibaki,

79
00:03:19,820 --> 00:03:21,820
had decided to pal up with

80
00:03:21,820 --> 00:03:23,820
the man that he was going to clean out,

81
00:03:23,820 --> 00:03:25,820
Daniel arap Moi,

82
00:03:25,820 --> 00:03:28,820
so this report then

83
00:03:28,820 --> 00:03:30,820
became a dead albatross

84
00:03:30,820 --> 00:03:33,820
around President Kibaki's neck.

85
00:03:34,820 --> 00:03:37,820
CA: And -- I mean, to cut a long story short --

86
00:03:37,820 --> 00:03:40,820
word of the report leaked into Kenya,

87
00:03:40,820 --> 00:03:43,820
not from the official media, but indirectly,

88
00:03:43,820 --> 00:03:46,820
and in your opinion, it actually shifted the election.

89
00:03:46,820 --> 00:03:49,820
JA: Yeah. So this became front page of the Guardian

90
00:03:49,820 --> 00:03:52,820
and was then printed in all the surrounding countries of Kenya,

91
00:03:52,820 --> 00:03:55,820
in Tanzanian and South African press.

92
00:03:55,820 --> 00:03:57,820
And so it came in from the outside.

93
00:03:57,820 --> 00:03:59,820
And that, after a couple of days,

94
00:03:59,820 --> 00:04:01,820
made the Kenyan press feel safe to talk about it.

95
00:04:01,820 --> 00:04:04,820
And it ran for 20 nights straight on Kenyan TV,

96
00:04:04,820 --> 00:04:07,820
shifted the vote by 10 percent,

97
00:04:07,820 --> 00:04:09,820
according to a Kenyan intelligence report,

98
00:04:09,820 --> 00:04:11,820
which changed the result of the election.

99
00:04:11,820 --> 00:04:13,820
CA: Wow, so your leak

100
00:04:13,820 --> 00:04:15,820
really substantially changed the world?

101
00:04:15,820 --> 00:04:17,820
JA: Yep.

102
00:04:17,820 --> 00:04:21,820
(Applause)

103
00:04:21,820 --> 00:04:23,820
CA: Here's -- We're going to just show

104
