and releasing 50.

165
00:06:58,820 --> 00:07:01,820
Now, we had released,

166
00:07:01,820 --> 00:07:03,820
early in the year,

167
00:07:03,820 --> 00:07:06,820
a cable from the Reykjavik U.S. embassy,

168
00:07:07,820 --> 00:07:09,820
but this is not necessarily connected.

169
00:07:09,820 --> 00:07:11,820
I mean, I was a known visitor of that embassy.

170
00:07:11,820 --> 00:07:13,820
CA: I mean, if you did receive thousands

171
00:07:13,820 --> 00:07:16,820
of U.S. embassy diplomatic cables ...

172
00:07:16,820 --> 00:07:18,820
JA: We would have released them. (CA: You would?)

173
00:07:18,820 --> 00:07:21,820
JA: Yeah. (CA: Because?)

174
00:07:21,820 --> 00:07:23,820
JA: Well, because these sort of things

175
00:07:23,820 --> 00:07:26,820
reveal what the true state

176
00:07:26,820 --> 00:07:28,820
of, say,

177
00:07:28,820 --> 00:07:30,820
Arab governments are like,

178
00:07:30,820 --> 00:07:33,820
the true human-rights abuses in those governments.

179
00:07:33,820 --> 00:07:35,820
If you look at declassified cables,

180
00:07:35,820 --> 00:07:37,820
that's the sort of material that's there.

181
00:07:37,820 --> 00:07:39,820
CA: So let's talk a little more broadly about this.

182
00:07:39,820 --> 00:07:41,820
I mean, in general, what's your philosophy?

183
00:07:41,820 --> 00:07:43,820
Why is it right

184
00:07:43,820 --> 00:07:46,820
to encourage leaking of secret information?

185
00:07:47,820 --> 00:07:50,820
JA: Well, there's a question as to what sort of information is important in the world,

186
00:07:50,820 --> 00:07:52,820
what sort of information

187
00:07:52,820 --> 00:07:54,820
can achieve reform.

188
00:07:54,820 --> 00:07:56,820
And there's a lot of information.

189
00:07:56,820 --> 00:07:58,820
So information that organizations

190
00:07:58,820 --> 00:08:01,820
are spending economic effort into concealing,

191
00:08:01,820 --> 00:08:03,820
that's a really good signal

192
00:08:03,820 --> 00:08:05,820
that when the information gets out,

193
00:08:05,820 --> 00:08:07,820
there's a hope of it doing some good --

194
00:08:07,820 --> 00:08:09,820
because the organizations that know it best,

195
00:08:09,820 --> 00:08:11,820
that know it from the inside out,

196
00:08:11,820 --> 00:08:14,820
are spending work to conceal it.

197
00:08:14,820 --> 00:08:16,820
And that's what we've found in practice,

198
00:08:16,820 --> 00:08:19,820
and that's what the history of journalism is.

199
00:08:19,820 --> 00:08:22,820
CA: But are there risks with that,

200
00:08:22,820 --> 00:08:25,820
either to the individuals concerned

201
00:08:25,820 --> 00:08:27,820
or indeed to society at large,

202
00:08:27,820 --> 00:08:29,820
where leaking can actually have

203
00:08:29,820 --> 00:08:31,820
an unintended consequence?

204
00:08:31,820 --> 00:08:33,820
JA: Not that we have seen with anything we have released.

205
00:08:33,820 --> 00:08:35,820
I mean, we have a harm immunization policy.

206
00:08:35,820 --> 00:08:37,820
We have a way of dealing with information

207
00:08:37,820 --> 00:08:39,820
that has sort of personal --

208
00:08:39,820 --> 00:08:41,820
personally identifying information in it.

209
00:08:42,820 --> 00:08:45,820
But there are legitimate secrets --

210
00:08:45,820 --> 00:08:48,820
you know, your records with your doctor;

211
00:08:48,820 --> 00:08:50,820
that's a legitimate secret --

212
00:08:50,820 --> 00:08:52,820
but we deal with whistleblowers that are coming forward

213
00:08:52,820 --> 00:08:55,820
that are really sort of well-motivated.

214
00:08:55,820 --> 00:08:57,820
CA: So they are well-motivated.

215
00:08:57,820 --> 00:08:59,820
And what would you say to, for example,

216
00:08:59,820 --> 00:09:02,820
the, you know, the parent of someone

217
00:09:02,820 --> 00:09:05,820
whose son is out serving the U.S. military,

218
00:09:05,820 --> 00:09:07,820
and he says, "You know what,

219
00:09:07,820 --> 00:09:09,820
you've put up something that someone had an incentive to put out.

220
00:09:09,820 --> 00:09:11,820
It shows a U.S. soldier laughing

221
00:09:11,820 --> 00:09:13,820
at people dying.

222
00:09:13,820 --> 00:09:15,820
That gives the impression, has given the impression,

223
00:09:15,820 --> 00:09:17,820
to millions of people around the world

224
00:09:17,820 --> 00:09:19,820
that U.S. soldiers are inhuman people.

225
00:09:19,820 --> 00:09:21,820
Actually, they're not. My son isn't. How dare you?"

226
00:09:21,820 --> 00:09:23,820
What would you say to that?

227
00:09:23,820 --> 00:09:25,820
JA: Yeah, we do get a lot of that.

228
00:09:25,820 --> 00:09:27,820
But remember, the people in Baghdad,

229
00:09:27,820 --> 00:09:30,820
the people in Iraq, the people in Afghanistan --

230
00:09:30,820 --> 00:09:32,820
they don't need to see the video;

231
00:09:32,820 --> 00:09:34,820
they see it every day.

232
00:09:34,820 --> 00:09:37,820
So it's not going to change their opinion. It's not going to change their perception.

233
00:09:37,820 --> 00:09:39,820
That's what they see every day.

234
00:09:39,820 --> 00:09:42,820
It will change the perception and opinion

235
00:09:42,820 --> 00:09:44,820
of the people who are paying for it all,

236
00:09:44,820 --> 00:09:47,820
and that's our hope.

237
00:09:47,820 --> 00:09:50,820
CA: So you found a way to shine light

238
00:09:50,820 --> 00:09:53,820
into what you see

239
00:09:53,820 --> 00:09:56,820
as these sort of dark secrets in companies and in government.

240
00:09:57,820 --> 00:09:59,820
Light is good.

241
00:09:59,820 --> 00:10:01,820
But do you see any irony in the fact that,

242
00:10:01,820 --> 00:10:03,820
in order for you to shine that light,

243
00:10:03,820 --> 00:10:05,820
you have to, yourself,

244
00:10:05,820 --> 00:10:08,820
create secrecy around your sources?

245
00:10:08,820 --> 00:10:11,820
JA: Not really. I mean, we don't have

246
00:10:11,820 --> 00:10:14,820
any WikiLeaks dissidents yet.

247
00:10:15,820 --> 00:10:18,820
We don't have sources who are dissidents on other sources.

248
00:10:19,820 --> 00:10:22,820
Should they come forward, that would be a tricky situation for us,

249
00:10:22,820 --> 00:10:25,820
but we're presumably acting in such a way

250
00:10:25,820 --> 00:10:27,820
that people feel

251
00:10:27,820 --> 00:10:29,820
morally compelled

252
00:10:29,820 --> 00:10:32,820
to continue our mission, not to screw it up.

253
00:10:33,820 --> 00:10:36,820
CA: I'd actually be interested, just based on what we've heard so far --

254
00:10:36,820 --> 00:10:39,820
I'm curious as to the opinion in the TED audience.

255
